'use strict';

/* ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   MOSAIK — picture excavation with color-container buckets

   Each level is a real picture (a procedurally-drawn scene, rendered to
   an actual PNG at real photo resolution, growing well past the 300x300
   floor at higher tiers — see scripts/generate-mosaik-levels.js — and
   shown as the reference image) reduced to a coarser interactive "sand"
   mosaic below it. The picture starts WHOLE; the game DECONSTRUCTS it,
   not reconstructs it.

   You don't tap individual pixels. Several bucket SLOTS are active at
   once (a level-scaled default, more unlockable via quiz questions, up to
   one per distinct color in the picture). You can only pick a color that
   currently has at least one REACHABLE pixel — the bottom `bandHeight`
   rows of the picture — so not every color is choosable at all times,
   only whatever's currently exposed; buried colors aren't options yet.

   Crucially, a single bucket does NOT hold an entire color's supply — its
   capacity is a modest fraction (MS_BUCKET_CAPACITY_FRACTION, ~12%) of
   that color's total count in the picture, so most colors take several
   separate bucket placements over the course of a level, not one. Once
   placed, a bucket passively drains its color from the reachable band
   (cascading across every active slot as gravity exposes more) until it
   either hits its own capacity or that color runs out entirely — either
   way the slot frees up, ready for a new placement (same color again, if
   more remains, or a different one).

   Columns are represented as an array of bottom-up color stacks, ALWAYS
   the same length as the grid's column count — a column that empties
   stays at its own fixed index, never dropped/shifted, so the picture's
   horizontal structure survives being dug into (unlike a same-color-match
   puzzle, which this is explicitly NOT).

   Why generation needs no combinatorial solver: using ALL `maxSlots`
   slots at once (one per distinct color), with FREE re-selection of
   whichever color just freed a slot, is solvable BY CONSTRUCTION —
   nothing is ever permanently blocked, since every remaining color keeps
   becoming reachable via gravity and can always be re-picked. The only
   real generation question is whether a level's tighter default (`db`,
   one fewer than maxSlots) is ALSO enough for at least one achievable
   strategy — scripts/generate-mosaik-levels.js answers that by simulating
   a real greedy playthrough (always assign the color with the most
   currently-reachable pixels to a free slot, repeating placements as
   buckets free up) via the actual functions below; scripts/verify-mosaik-
   levels.js independently re-runs the same simulation against the real
   shipped functions before a level ships.

   "Stuck" = every unlocked slot is occupied AND none of their colors
   currently has anything reachable AND the picture isn't cleared — the
   rescue is the same as every other mini-game: a toast pointing at
   Restart, or spend a quiz question to unlock one more slot (mirrors
   Water Sort's extra-bottle / Parkplatz's extra-bay mechanic exactly,
   feeding the Tamagotchi for free via the shared askQuestions()).

   Levels are static data (MS_LEVELS below). Only the shuffled play
   order/position and the LIVE in-progress columns/slot state are
   persisted in the save; level layouts (and their PNG reference images)
   ship with the app.
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

const MS_COLORS = [
  "#a8d8e8", // 0: sky
  "#e8d95a", // 1: sun/moon glow
  "#6fd88a", // 2: foliage
  "#c9a857", // 3: bark/ground
  "#3a3a4a", // 4: silhouette/dark
  "#e0413a", // 5: accent red
  "#b06fe8", // 6: accent purple
];
const MS_MAX_EXTRA_SLOTS = 3; // mirrors Water Sort's WS_MAX_EXTRA_BOTTLES
const MS_BUCKET_CAPACITY_FRACTION = 0.12; // one bucket holds ~12% of a color's total — never the whole thing

